<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-14T13:43:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-14T13:43:00-05:00" n="1132" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1132">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72111W74/3</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Liberia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BGW1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Buckner</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">Monrovia</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-14T18:00:00-00:43">
                                <hi rend="italic">August 14, 1914, 6 pm.</hi>
                            </date>[<hi rend="italic">Received 11 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>French Government demands that German wireless be closed or neutrality
                            would not be observed according to the Hague Convention V, 1907,
                            Articles 3, 5, and 25. French wireless still open. Liberian Government
                            desires advice.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_HMT1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Buckner</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>